******
[1] Manipur state
Date: Sat 23 Jul 2016
Source: The Telegraph [edited]
http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160724/jsp/northeast/story_98422.jsp#.V5aKo1dLWOo


The Manipur health department today [23 Jul 2016] confirmed an outbreak of Japanese encephalitis in the state with the detection of 9 positive cases across 6 districts.

Director of the health department Okram Ibomcha Singh said 9 positive cases had been confirmed so far, and more blood samples are being examined. He, however, clarified that the outbreak has not taken the form of an epidemic. The positive cases are reported from the districts of Thoubal, Imphal West, Churachandpur, Chandel, Ukhrul and Imphal East. One of the patients resides on the outskirts of Imphal city.

Of the 9 patients, 8 are undergoing treatment at Jawaharlal Nehru Institute of Medical Sciences and Regional Institute of Medical Sciences here free of cost, while the other patient is undergoing treatment at a hospital outside the state. Official sources said there are more suspected cases. The exact number of positive cases would be known after the laboratory test of the blood samples.

Ibomcha said it was not wise for Japanese encephalitis patients to seek treatment at private hospitals.

"All possible steps have been taken to control the spread of the virus causing the disease. There is no reason for panic. We are fighting the outbreak on a war footing," Ibomcha Singh said.

The official said that 3000 vials or 15 000 doses of anti-Japanese encephalitis vaccine are in stock at present and 75 000 doses would be arriving in a few days to increase the stock.

Fogging has already been initiated to kill mosquitoes within a 2-km radius of the localities from where the positive cases were reported.

Manipur has experienced an outbreak of the disease in the past. According to official records, there were 200 cases in 1995; 50 affected people died that year. Out of 100 positive cases in 2010, 10 patients died. There were 9 positive cases last year [2015].

Health minister D.K. Korungthan, accompanied by the health director, visited primary health centres yesterday [22 Jul 2016] located in Chandel district, one of the affected districts, and distributed anti-Japanese encephalitis vaccines. The team also supervised the ongoing fogging activities in the district.

The health minister appealed to the people not to panic, assuring them the state government had taken all possible measures. He also advised people to protect themselves from mosquitoes.

[Byline: Khelen Thokchom]

