******
[2] Odisha state
Date: Sun 24 Jul 2016
Source: The New Indian Express [edited]
http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/Japanese-Encephalitis-virus-surfaces/2016/07/24/article3544622.ece


After the spurt in dengue cases in 24 districts of the state, Japanese encephalitis, a viral disease, has been detected in 3 villages under Brahmagiri block of Puri district.

An expert team of the Animal Disease Research Institute (ADRI) has visited the affected villages of Khilla Kanthia, Toranapada and Mulabari for surveillance on the disease in pigs.

The team collected serum samples from 6 apparently healthy pigs, out of which 3 samples were found to be positive for Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) [antibodies] by enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) test at Bareilly-based Indian Veterinary Research Institute (IVRI). In fact, pigs as well as certain wild birds (Heron) act as the carriers of JEV. There is no mortality in adult pigs except of reproductive symptoms like abortion, mummified foetus and still births, but in piglets, mortality may go up to 100 percent. From these carriers, the disease is transmitted not by contact but by the vector mosquitoes (species in the genus _Culex_ and _Aedes_), which are usually active during dusk and dawn.

"That's why vector control has much importance to prevent the transmission of virus from pig to pig and pig to human. Pigs may be reared away from human habitation to minimise the chance of human infection," stated an ADRI official.

Japanese encephalitis is caused by a mosquito-borne virus. This disease is mostly seen in humans during the mosquitoes' breeding season. Now nearly 18 states have recorded JEV and acute encephalitis syndrome (AES), which have high mortality and morbidity rates.

In Odisha, the 1st outbreak was reported in 2012 in Malkangiri district. At least 24 children had died in Potrel and Uskapalli villages under Chitrakonda tehsil and Pradhaniguda and Charkiguda villages under Malkangiri tehsil.

There is no vaccine [not accurate; there is a JEV vaccine that is widely used in India. - Mod.TY] and specific anti-viral medicine available against JEV in humans. The cases are managed symptomatically. Clinical management is supportive, and acute care is directed at maintaining fluid, electrolyte balance and control of convulsions, if present. Maintenance of airway is crucial.

The preventive measures are directed at reducing the vector density and in taking personal protection against mosquito bites using insecticide treated mosquito nets. The reduction in mosquito breeding requires eco-management, as the role of insecticides is limited.

